{"result": "{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter X: Life-Cycle Costing Analysis for Nuclear and Wind Power Stations at Volt Co\",\n    \"summary\": \"This chapter delves into the life-cycle costing analysis for nuclear and wind power stations at Volt Co. It covers the comprehensive evaluation of operating costs, decommissioning costs, and the total life-cycle cost per gigawatt for both types of power stations. The chapter also discusses the disposal cost of spent nuclear fuel, categorized as an internal failure cost in environmental management accounting (EMA). Key methodologies include the calculation of life-cycle costs for nuclear and wind stations, and the integration of environmental management accounting principles.\",\n    \"rating\": 8.5,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The chapter is highly significant due to its detailed analysis of life-cycle costs in the context of environmental management accounting, which is crucial for sustainable business practices.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Life-cycle costing analysis for nuclear and wind power stations\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter provides an in-depth analysis of the life-cycle costs associated with nuclear and wind power stations at Volt Co. This includes operating costs, decommissioning costs, and the total life-cycle cost per gigawatt. The life-cycle cost per gigawatt for a nuclear station is calculated as the total life-cycle costs divided by the total gigawatts generated over the station's useful life [Data: Concepts (1584)]. Similarly, the life-cycle cost per gigawatt for a wind station is calculated using the same formula [Data: Concepts (1585)]. This comprehensive approach ensures that all costs incurred over the life of the power stations are accounted for, providing a clear picture of their economic viability [Data: Concepts (1583); Relationships (1502, 1503)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Disposal cost of spent nuclear fuel\",\n        